V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree ride is achieved by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant faults to the routine ride to the early shift.
Although it has succeeded in fulfilling the ambitions to a large extent, what is useful if no one obviously wanted to do a little more.
Before he got to the shop tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already-agened series of games "need for speed" again into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the matching passages are going, in which the main protagonist rises out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you're used to at NFS, in the final effect, it's much different than you expected.
Sure - it's potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some excess errors that have been present in this series for more or less years.
So it's actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of an incomprehensib laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into the story, whose main character Jack has some personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different route and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't have the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very beautiful, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing moving around the world.
But the journey through the desert, through autumny landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape works visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, unusual elements bring a little variety into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that greatly limits the view.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be very careful not to be thrown away by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in succession.
Just a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have to pick up time (classical race against the stopwatch), then expect another personal duel with a single competitor.
And the police are also interfering, trying to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about some interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much less passages in the game than you would expect (almost only three).
Finally, this is more to the advantage of the matter, because this element at least has no chance of getting bored - it is in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model runs into the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, it does not rip trees, on the other hand, it could not be said that it would be bad.
Those looking for realistic simulations have to look around elsewhere.
But the local driving model will continue to be quite fair to an action-loaded race, although one could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems appear only after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
A game of this kind can hardly be expected to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you don't have virtually any impact on any object idea how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: In the tight overtaking or passing by oncoming cars, you "stir" the other car in some places only easy, but in other, almost identical situation you get into sluggish and spin wild pirouettes.
Or the cart will go straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, from annoyance it's all the time.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, you throw the game back at the last point of reference of the track.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
When you've exhausted them, everything goes from the front.
So the restarts are more like an aid, in case something fails, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the restart helps, there is nothing else but to learn the critical section from the head.
Pronouncedly, the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, have to pass through in a very specific way, otherwise you simply don't pass through.
Elsewhere you always meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you are coming as first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoyed in situations when you see that the opponent comes by in front of a playful car, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that it always comes close to your nose.
Contractors have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same time and here again without regard to the time.
The most crazy thing is to finish the game on the long bridge that happens in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to catch up with one of these devils.
And if he's already in front of you, then he'll take a look at you, so you start driving your own car in Klump a few times.
Clearly - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly rents you the joy of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite a simple driving model, the game as a whole is quite entertaining and sometimes so action-loaded that you almost no longer know where one's head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "debt" it is - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can occur, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car in the course of the race.
You must not overlook the gas stations on the track, because just here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical journeys, for example on the Serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history also the task mode (exhibitions) - i.e. the races in the individual locations you know from history.
Here there are not only medals, but also points to gain experience for one's own profile, which is common for the tasks (expressions) and history.
To get to the higher level of the driver, different items must be unlocked: starting from the car, up to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is connected at the same time to the Autolog online function, which compares, among other things, its own results with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (meineway), where you race in the dark on the rails for long (meine).
On the tacho, numbers between 150 a 200 km/h (meineway), but there is a subway coming from the rear and driving to scrap without compromise.
In our editorial team, we will probably be fighting for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
The more annoyed it is that at some exciting moments the frequency of the image is slowing down and sometimes this is quite dramatic.
However, this concerns in particular accidents involving a greater number of persons, where continuous FPS is no use at all.
The sound reproduction is O.K. and the soundtrack is tasteful.
In the effort to address a scale as broad as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "of every thing" arose - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game would not be reduced by the mentioned totally unnecessary errors, we could have asserted with the breasttone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game looks somehow unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to put these mistakes in one's eyes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Same Revolution" with vocal ensembles of the Karlsuniversität
For the third time now, the Festival Festa Academica offers the refreshment of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samten Revolution and this along with music experience.
During the festival, the twenty professorships and university choirs will present themselves.
The main focus of the festival is the two concerts, which will take place on 17 November.
"Karlsuniversität has a large share in the festival."
"Among the participants is also represented by the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies and the festival committee is also attended by the rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organization team.
The highlight of the festival is the public concert of specialist school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 2 pm on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazzist Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening hours, the concert "Students of the American Revolution" (Students of the American Revolution) will take place in the gala rooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, where university choirs will also be held, not excluding choirs of the Karlsuniversity.
Festa Academica sets itself the goal not only to celebrate the World Student Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Samten Revolution, but to present choir music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative collaboration of young people.
The main organizer is the association of Czech choirs in cooperation with the Johannes-Kepler-Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital Prague and Václav Hampl, the rector of the Karlsuniversity, took over the entire event.
The festival will take place from 16th to 20th November in Prague and in Pardubice.
The schedule includes, apart from festival concerts, numerous music meetings, student menus, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
