IBM History: From cheese cutter to global flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) had a rather complicated name at first - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM only took over the name in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone to the later society of IBM laid the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They owned technologies such as the famous stech card watches for registration of the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who appointed the head of competition firm Thomas J. Watson to help him in the management of the company.
This leader then even put IBM's founders in the shadows - on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, began, as already the name reveals, with the production and distribution of all kinds of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to checkouts.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he was sitting in the chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped lead NASA flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight from man to the moon.
Meanwhile IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, came into the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to Lenovo Chinese company, but on the other hand bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered into the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of "smart planet".
