Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised public travel agencies in the ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold only travel to the socialist eastern blocklands, and in the West only were allowed to choose.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the eastern block (i.e. also the Czechoslovakian) to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called letter of invitation, otherwise individual trips would not be possible.
Even then the travel agencies also offered travel to the west, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintance" in the travel agency.
This is the same thing that had not yet been done.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for an exit to the West - was only granted "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Thus, most Czechs spent their vacation in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dasschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The same revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox of which one is no longer aware today is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday destination in the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe, which caused a tremendous wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, the Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their travels to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a guest house at that time.
A typical feature on travel abroad from the Czech Republic was a box with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and thus average salaries increased, resulting in a further important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 travel agencies began to prepare regularly trips through charter flights, which, thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts, made them incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the United States, the Czechs had already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-autumn" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-away sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flyn directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17th, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely led our country to join the advanced countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost at the resort.
