Stories about fraud in school and college exams are widespread.
There were incidents in which teachers gave their students the exam answers so that they could even do well in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheats are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies show, we lie between 10 and 200 times every day.
Many of these lies, however, are regarded as emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognising lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important for everyone to learn, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a game of society, such as puberty, in which the goal is to call "Be!", detachment of a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out extensive research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most old myths were degenerated about lying.
Lies look into your eyes.
They don't always stutter, stem, roast, and snack.
But it must not be concluded that these liars are hard to reveal and defuse.
A trained liar can penetrate the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, the questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of detarcation. And it is clear that detangling a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to find comfort in our complex world, especially if the setting up or questioning of persons or negotiations or administration are among our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, their interest and their own emotions, and they feel intuitive as they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men appear more often "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "orientated to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been degenerated as an evildoer, others feel less guilty to have lied to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First of all, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
That's called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your test person.
You should know better when someone normally trips with his foot constantly, so that they do not accuse him unjustly if he drops his foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells, which shrill, not as evidence of detachment.
People who cheat may stare when they try to remember their story. Perhaps their feet point toward the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relax after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhale and change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that a job interview is over, just to look after the job interview after this relaxation.
Also take care of the language of your test person.
Scott Peterson's slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Diving persons can also use a distant language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I am aware ... to the best of knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, which often makes the alarm bells shriek.
There is no magic means for detachment of lies, but one can learn skills through which detachment is possible.
Thanks to these skills, each individual can become a victim of fraud, both in private and in professional life.
