Climate resistance slowed the economy down
In the first year, where Mario López Valdez is at the government, unemployment and black-and-collar work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, Sinaloas will be remembered in economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and is a source of great hopes regarding economic growth, is on the government. However, as a result of the climateic contradictions, growth cannot be the case, but on the contrary, the most important economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also close limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year, mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 3116 percent, which slowed down on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed. It was mainly concerned with vegetable, corn and chick pea cultivation.
The decline in economic activity by November has continued to increase unemployment in the Mexican state. In the first quarter, the Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment, since from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6,19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18 969 people over the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa dates back to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of the public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are observing today is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, losses in liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in funds due to the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are forbidden to raise dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or otherwise use them," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, due to the problems of entry and, on the one hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here looking for work, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Unworked work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of the employees working in the country without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaryía del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
ADI decrease
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the highest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaryía de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to 630 597 dollars from January to June, equivalent to 87.74 percent in comparison to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
The Secretaryía de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) for its part recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 Pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debts
In the light of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July to reactivate the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
The first year of government of Mario López Valdé's inability to rule made clear to the representatives of the entrepreneurship.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Processing Industry in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the various sectors, including the national government.
