Asphalt by UNAM prevents hitholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM University of Mexico, develops polymer modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs were to be taken from the street floor, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 hitholes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the layout and maintenance of the asphalt covering was appropriate, the number of hitholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture, "Treasureholes from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory, for which he is responsible, develops asphalt modified polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which, however, has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the street floor and thus avoid the occurrence of punching holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most heavy part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which have a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malts. Together they give the road covering its characteristic toughening behavior.
Tail elastic behavior of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very soft and at 50°C almost solid, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resilience of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ's researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible street covering, which consisted of six layers of materials, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this layer of wear, had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on and the forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road covering.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"On the wear layer," he explained, "is designed a final layer, the so-called carrier consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
The majority of the forces that receive and distribute this road covering also require an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates into the layer and becomes difficult again. This causes all layers of the street floor and as a result the occurrence of impact holes.
When a punchhole is created," he said, "the cover layer is initially removed, while the wear layer is only affected after that. But the damage is not immediately caused, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sisthema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road covering must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research projects were still waiting for him, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the hit holes could be repaired easily and without using high temperatures.
