Austria
Entry of a "golden household rule" into the Constitution
On Tuesday the Austrian government of the Great Socialist/Christian Democratic Coalition decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid any degradation by rating agencies in the top bond of Austria (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who had announced this decision of the Council of Ministers, although the public debt of Austria is 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of the countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the payment capacity of Austria had not fallen at a stroke from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Foreign Minister.
Austria is also calling for the Brussels Summit of the Member States of the Eurozone of 26 October: the Heads of State or Government would then have demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government is similar to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to have included such a "rule" in the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should fall by 0.75% of GDP each year, while from 2017 onwards, the structural deficit of the state should not exceed the 0.35% of GDP, whereas the regional states as well as the municipalities should have balanced households.
The aim is to eliminate budgetary debt in the horizon of 2020/21 under the 60% criterion set out in the Maastricht Agreement.
