But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
On this issue there is a broad consensus between the right and the left.
On the right, Jacques Chirac's tone, which had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including more than 2 million immigrants, are not likely to pose a problem for a country", was declared by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "can't take up the world's entire poverty".
Only difference exists in the degree of greatness
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hoards of Polish plumbers was shared by both right and left in 2005.
The immigrants were perceived by both camps as a burden for the economy and the French society.
The only difference is to the extent that there is a desire to express to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande is limited to banalities pointing out that partnership development allows us to solve our "immigration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections; however, it is cost-effective economically.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present in a recently published work, which summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists regarding the positive impact of the immigrant flood on economic growth, wages and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Limiting immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute local workers, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than domestic wage workers, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors which are unburdened at work.
The low-qualified immigrants work in sectors where local wage workers are not very attractive, the more skilled among immigrants are working in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anaesthetics, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and national labour market situation between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the immigrant flood resulted in a co-related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas and economic growth introduced by immigrants is contributing (high proportion of indigenous immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to the social systems, in the European countries, on average, about 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that an immigrant aged 30 to Germany, on average, brings a net contribution (incomes minus expenditure) to the public budget of around 150,000 euros over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with his teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, were exactly the opposite effect.
