"Contactless" Chip Cards Become the General Good
On Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris, the world trade fair for chip cards opens its gates in an optimistic manner.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is the contactless technology, which enables payments in public transport or charging of purchases by simply keeping the card to a reader.
This year 460 million contactless chip cards were sold this year compared to 320 million sold a year earlier!
Its market share should continue to increase in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent more than 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe wins with regard to the contactless payment to the ground after it has been behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time.
Some 26 million visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept them.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
However, consumer markets are steaming.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move faster, it is now necessary that banks equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically hand over bank cards with contactless chip to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director-General of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A disappearingly low percentage of devices have so far been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology required to carry out these transactions.
"They're in arrears."
"But they should experience a real upward trend at least next year."
"We expect to sell from 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012, says Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale also said yesterday to prepare the market launch of an offer that allows their customers to pay without contact by phone.
