North Stream, New Gate to Russian Gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the sea floor of the Baltic Sea and connects the Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is said to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to commit this event with shine and gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at fine tasting buffet the initiation of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level.
German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically turned together the control of the valve, which transports the Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is intended to deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year through a first 1.224 km long pipeline connecting the Sankt Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And one already makes the possibility of building a third line sound on its own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and point-specific completion of this huge structure seems like a victory.
The project was strongly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land road.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close the entry to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most involved in the debate, was not retreaded to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet Pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of decommissioning European energy, as the project has broken between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries with strong gas consumption and their gas reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new arteries that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the initiation of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the wide smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin with regard to the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at a depth of about 200 m.
During their construction, mine fields dating from the Second World War had to be removed.
"Approximately hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for the sake of caution," stated Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream Society.
In addition, increased measures to protect fauna and flora had to be taken.
The line is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything throughout the length: neither through valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have distanced themselves from it, as the Sweden had little desire to see a Russian state company settled in a permanent manner at the level of its coasts.
"In the case of a harry, we close the gas through in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the case of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline disappears into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors as little likely, since the welds were estimated to be a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The State monitoring of the gas pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes by a seaship, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures a meter in diameter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit.
Five societies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are subdivided ( each to 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gas Union and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport, on renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the really transported amount of gas is", explained Jens Müller.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured 30% of shareholders as well as 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For example, for GDF Suez, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are able to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline appears on a sandy, pine forested coastline at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas outlets.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
